vpc
A VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) in AWS is your own isolated section of the cloud — like a private data center inside AWS — where you define your own network configuration, IP ranges, subnets, and routing rules.

🧩 Core Concepts of VPC
Component	Description	Example
CIDR Block	Defines the IP range for your VPC.	10.0.0.0/16
Subnets	Divide the VPC into smaller networks — public and private.	10.0.1.0/24 (public), 10.0.2.0/24 (private)
Route Tables	Control how traffic flows between subnets and the internet.	Route to 0.0.0.0/0 via Internet Gateway
Internet Gateway (IGW)	Enables communication between your VPC and the internet.	Attached to public subnets
NAT Gateway	Allows private instances to access the internet securely.	Used for outbound traffic only
Security Groups	Instance-level firewalls controlling inbound/outbound traffic.	Allow SSH (port 22)
Network ACLs (NACLs)	Subnet-level firewalls for additional security.	Deny all traffic except HTTP/HTTPS


⚙️ How It Works
You create a VPC with a CIDR block (e.g., 10.0.0.0/16).

Inside it, you define subnets — public (internet-facing) and private (internal).

Attach an Internet Gateway for public access.

Use a NAT Gateway for private instances to reach the internet.

Configure route tables to direct traffic appropriately.

Secure everything with Security Groups and NACLs.

🌐 Example Flow
A user accesses your web app → request hits public subnet (EC2 + Elastic IP).

The app server in the private subnet connects to a database (RDS) internally.

Outbound updates or patches go through the NAT Gateway.

